<!-- SECTION 10: GLOSSARY -->
<section id="glossary">
<div class="section-inner">
<div class="section-header hidden">
<p class="section-num">10 / GLOSSARY</p>
<h2>Glossary</h2>
<p class="thesis">The language of sound made visible.</p>
</div>
<div class="glossary-grid">
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-0"><div class="glossary-term">FFT</div><div class="glossary-def">Fast Fourier Transform. An algorithm that converts a time-domain signal into its constituent frequencies in O(n log n) time. The foundation of all audio analysis.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-1"><div class="glossary-term">Frequency Bin</div><div class="glossary-def">One output cell of the FFT. Each bin represents a narrow frequency range; its value is the amplitude of that frequency in the current analysis window.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-2"><div class="glossary-term">Spectral Centroid</div><div class="glossary-def">The "center of mass" of the frequency spectrum. High centroid = bright, treble-heavy sound. Low centroid = dark, bass-heavy. Correlates strongly with perceived timbre.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-3"><div class="glossary-term">Onset Detection</div><div class="glossary-def">The identification of the moment a new note or sound event begins. Computed by measuring sudden increases in spectral flux (change in energy between frames).</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-0"><div class="glossary-term">Beat Detection</div><div class="glossary-def">Identifying rhythmic pulse in music, typically by monitoring low-frequency energy and detecting when it exceeds a threshold relative to the recent energy average.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-1"><div class="glossary-term">RMS</div><div class="glossary-def">Root Mean Square. The square root of the mean of squared sample values. A perceptually accurate measure of loudness, corresponding closely to how humans perceive volume.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-2"><div class="glossary-term">Spectrogram</div><div class="glossary-def">A 2D visualization showing time on the X axis, frequency on the Y axis, and amplitude encoded as color. Makes the harmonic and temporal structure of sound visible simultaneously.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-3"><div class="glossary-term">Waterfall Display</div><div class="glossary-def">A scrolling spectrogram that continuously moves the historical data to reveal new analysis. Named for its resemblance to falling water when amplitude is high.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-0"><div class="glossary-term">Lissajous Figure</div><div class="glossary-def">A curve traced by plotting two sinusoidal signals against each other on X and Y axes. Used in audio as a stereo vectorscope — the shape reveals phase relationships between channels.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-1"><div class="glossary-term">Audio Reactivity</div><div class="glossary-def">The technique of extracting real-time features from audio signals and using them to drive visual parameters. The core discipline of this entire field.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-2"><div class="glossary-term">Parameter Mapping</div><div class="glossary-def">The deliberate assignment of audio features to visual parameters. The creative act that defines audiovisual work — the "what controls what" decision.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-3"><div class="glossary-term">GLSL Shader</div><div class="glossary-def">OpenGL Shading Language. A C-like language that runs on the GPU, executing in parallel for every pixel simultaneously. Enables real-time complex visual effects.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-0"><div class="glossary-term">Uniform Variable</div><div class="glossary-def">In GLSL, a variable that remains constant for an entire frame but can be updated between frames. Audio features are typically passed to shaders as uniforms.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-1"><div class="glossary-term">Mel Scale</div><div class="glossary-def">A perceptual frequency scale where equal distances correspond to equal perceived pitch differences. More bins at low frequencies where human hearing has higher resolution.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-2"><div class="glossary-term">Chromagram</div><div class="glossary-def">A representation of audio that collapses all octaves into 12 pitch classes (C through B). Reveals harmonic content and chord progressions independent of octave.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-3"><div class="glossary-term">Synesthesia</div><div class="glossary-def">A neurological phenomenon where one sensory pathway triggers automatic experiences in another — sound producing color, for example. Experienced by ~4% of the population.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-0"><div class="glossary-term">Envelope Following</div><div class="glossary-def">Tracking the amplitude contour of a signal over time. The envelope describes attack, decay, sustain, and release — the shape of sound as opposed to its pitch or timbre.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-1"><div class="glossary-term">Threshold</div><div class="glossary-def">A level value that triggers an action when crossed. In beat detection and Ryoji-style visualization, the threshold is the sole creative parameter — everything else is the music.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-2"><div class="glossary-term">Lag Filter</div><div class="glossary-def">A smoothing technique that makes values follow their targets gradually rather than instantly. Prevents visual jitter and creates organic motion: new = old + (target - old) × rate.</div></div>
<div class="glossary-card hidden stagger-3"><div class="glossary-term">Real-Time</div><div class="glossary-def">Processing that keeps pace with live input — completing each analysis frame faster than the next frame arrives. Typically 60fps (16.7ms per frame) for smooth visual output.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
